@jiangtaoli2016 I rebased to fix the conflicts and addressed @pmarks-net concerns about the allocation (but haven't tested yet).

I did spend a bit of time looking into whether this could viably go in `gpr_split_host_port`. Unfortunately there would be extra work required because the result of `gpr_split_host_port` is used to build the address structures and the expectation is that zone-id is retained. One could entertain modifying `gpr_split_host_port` such that it returns host, zone-id, and port which would mean logic to locate the `%` character could be consolidated and the `sockaddr_in6` creation code cleaned up a tad. But the behavior of security connector comparisons is affected by the presence of a zone-id and host%zone-id would need to be smashed back together when populating target_address (or the old function retained and used), which is annoying.

As a slight side note: I'm not familiar with exactly how the result of comparing security connectors is used functionally throughout grpc, but it strikes me that since port is stripped from the target address when creating a security connector, two connectors pointing at the same host but different ports would compare equal (unless something in their base layers prevents that). However, you generally can't assume one host would have the same security parameters for every service it's serving. If grpc were using these comparisons to make security decisions, this _could_ be a security issue. Or perhaps there could be a latent functional issue when using multiple grpc channels to connect to the same host.
